<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1700,2007]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,152,458]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,455,1821,1847]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Biology and ecology.</emphasis>
All specimens known so far have been found under big stones partially dug in the soil, on the coastal cliffs of a single locality at the north of Tenerife. The environment is highly influenced by marine spray, with halophilous vegetation mainly dominated by 
<taxonomicName box="[908,1164,1901,1926]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Crithmum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maritimum">
<emphasis box="[908,1164,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Crithmum maritimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName box="[1212,1436,1901,1926]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Astydamia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="latifolia">
<emphasis box="[1212,1436,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Astydamia latifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L. f.) Baill., 
<taxonomicName box="[309,431,1941,1966]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" genus="Frankenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[309,431,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Frankenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., 
<taxonomicName box="[488,586,1941,1966]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Sonchus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[488,586,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Sonchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ker. Gawl.) Haw." authorityName="(Ker. Gawl.) Haw." box="[643,1056,1941,1967]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dillenii">
<emphasis box="[643,831,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Opuntia dillenii</emphasis>
(Ker. Gawl.) Haw.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Willd. The" authorityName="Willd. The" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Tamaricaceae" genus="Tamarix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="canariensis">
<emphasis box="[1115,1355,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Tamarix canariensis</emphasis>
Willd. The
</taxonomicName>
soil is a vertisol of montmorillonitic clay, very different to that in places of La Palma and El Hierro where 
<taxonomicName box="[151,231,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baezia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,231,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Baezia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have ben found in lava tubes (
<bibRefCitation author="Alonso-Zarazaga" box="[685,1095,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="55" refString="Alonso-Zarazaga, M. A. &amp; Garcia, R. (1999) Baezia litoralis gen. n. y sp. n. de coleoptero edafobio de la isla de Tenerife (Col. Curculionidae, Molytinae). Vulcania, 3, 48 - 55." type="journal article" year="1999">
Alonso-Zarazaga and García 
<number box="[1032,1095,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These clays become highly cracked in dry periods, being a peculiar microhabitat where small endogean insects are living, like 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baezia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="litoralis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Baezia litoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the ground beetle 
<taxonomicName authority="Machado, 1992" authorityName="Machado" authorityYear="1992" box="[487,1145,232,258]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Parazuphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="damascenum" subSpecies="canariense">
<emphasis box="[487,946,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Parazuphium damascenum canariense</emphasis>
Machado, 
<number box="[1083,1145,232,258]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</taxonomicName>
. During the heavy rains this soil becomes muddy and the cracks get flooded, compelling this fauna to migrate to the surface. This is the best opportunity to find 
<taxonomicName box="[476,655,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baezia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="litoralis">
<emphasis box="[476,655,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Baezia litoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it probably leaves the flooded surroundings of the roots to shelter in stones with abundant alveoles free of water.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,152,458]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
No relations have been established between the collected specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1055,1237,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baezia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="litoralis">
<emphasis box="[1055,1237,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Baezia litoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the roots of any particular plant, but very probable it is also a rhizophagous species.
</paragraph>
